  <learning_objectives level="bloom_taxonomy">
    <objective level="remember" measurable="true">Define cryptographic service availability and key terms including resilience, disruption, Cryptographic Key Management System (CKMS), and availability in the CIA Triad.</objective>
    <objective level="remember" measurable="true">List the primary sources of disruptions to cryptographic services (e.g., hardware failures, DoS attacks, natural disasters).</objective>
    <objective level="understand" measurable="true">Explain how NIST SP 800-130 addresses availability in CKMS design, including disaster recovery and failure management.</objective>
    <objective level="understand" measurable="true">Describe the relationship between cryptographic service availability and the broader CIA Triad, particularly how disruptions impact confidentiality and integrity.</objective>
    <objective level="apply" measurable="true">Apply NIST SP 800-130 guidelines to outline a basic failover procedure for a cryptographic service outage.</objective>
    <objective level="analyze" measurable="true">Analyze the impact of a specific disruption (e.g., HSM hardware failure) on cryptographic operations and identify mitigation priorities.</objective>
    <objective level="evaluate" measurable="true">Evaluate the effectiveness of redundancy strategies (e.g., clustered HSMs) versus backup keys in achieving 99.9% CKMS availability.</objective>
    <objective level="create" measurable="true">Design a disaster recovery plan for a CKMS that integrates monitoring, automated failover, and testing to ensure high availability.</objective>
  </learning_objectives>
