    <layer level="1" name="Layer 1">
      <focus/>
      <content>Definitions: Cryptographic service availability (accessible/functional crypto functions on demand); Cryptographic service (encryption, signing, key mgmt); Disruption (hardware/software failure, network outage, DoS, disasters); Resilience (withstand/recover from disruptions). Core Concepts: Ties to CIA Availability; ensures crypto protections (confidentiality/integrity/auth) are always operational. Concept Map: Central 'Cryptographic Service Availability' → Branches: Definitions, Threats/Disruptions.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="2" name="Layer 2">
      <focus/>
      <content>NIST SP 800-130: Framework for CKMS design emphasizing availability goals—disaster recovery, hardware/software failure management, cryptographic service continuity, redundancy, monitoring. Other: NIST SP 800-57 (key lifecycle availability), FIPS 140 (module reliability). Concept Map Extensions: → NIST Controls (DR plans, failover), Relationships (CKMS components interdependencies).</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="3" name="Layer 3">
      <focus/>
      <content>Step-by-step: 1) Risk assessment for disruptions; 2) Implement redundancy (e.g., HSM clustering); 3) Automated failover/backup keys; 4) Monitoring/alerting; 5) Regular DR testing. Procedures: Failure handling (graceful degradation), recovery time objectives (RTO/RPO).</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="4" name="Layer 4">
      <focus/>
      <content>Optimization: Achieve 99.9%+ uptime via geo-redundancy, cloud HSMs (e.g., AWS KMS). Cross-domain: Zero-trust integration, DevSecOps key rotation. Advanced: AI-driven anomaly detection for proactive resilience.</content>
    </layer>
  </scaffolding>
